					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/misterflames" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(438028); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=438028&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252530" alt="MisterFlames" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=438028)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/misterflames" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(438028); return false;" >MisterFlames</a></span> <span class="odate time_1272737483 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 May 2010 18:11</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-771825">
									

<p>Thank you, Leicontis, that's precisely what I meant. That, and I do believe articles should have a measure of self-sufficiency.</p>
<p>Now mail concerning other SCPs I could see, but they would need to be exceptional and not break the other article. Mailing an instruction manual to Dr. Gears about <a href="/scp-914">SCP-914</a>, for instance, is right out. Same with dealing with <a href="/scp-682">SCP-682</a>, really.</p>
<p>I personally think the noteworthy mail would have a sort of emotional resonance about it. A lot of the mail that appears would be almost literally junk mail, just like the mail that shows up in your own mail boxes. The Foundation would just glance over it to see if there was anything of interest, then dispose of it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
